      "body":"## “Support partial bolded blocks”\r\n\r\nDon't worry about working on this: I got partially-formatted blocks of all existing types already working locally and plan to publish my PR of it tomorrow (edit: it will be PR #88). I tried editing my local code to include your support for bold, and the partially-bold line on [this page](http://localhost:3000/#/page/a58yqahTE) renders fine:\r\n\r\n![bold as part of a block working in my local branch](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/79168/82718490-cabee600-9c70-11ea-9790-2ecc8c1b727c.png)\r\n\r\nYou did well to make your parse rule match the format of the existing ones: it made it easy to integrate with my changes.\r\n\r\n## “Support nested bolded text”\r\n\r\nThis feature makes sense and we should probably have it eventually. But it would be easier to implement after my partial bolded blocks branch is merged, so I think you can wait.\r\n\r\nInterestingly, Roam doesn't fully implement this feature. It seems Roam doesn't allow most types formatting within bold, but it does allow italics:\r\n\r\n![bold nesting tests in Roam](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/79168/82718053-20de5a00-9c6e-11ea-9feb-3c36b95d0c47.png)\r\n\r\n## “add a simple test case to catch future regressions”\r\n\r\nI tried setting up local tests of the parser on my branch but gave up when it seemed too much trouble. I can tell you what I did and where I ran into trouble:\r\n\r\n1. Move `src/cljs/athens/parser.cljs` to `src/cljc/athens/parser.cljc`\r\n1. Create `src/test/athens/parser-test.clj` and pattern it off the other tests in that folder\r\n1. Then I noticed that `parser.cljc` was getting a parse error. This parse error was related to new code in my local branch: I used a ClojureScript-only form `:refer-macros` to import the `defparser` macro. Because of that form, the file couldn't be compiled as `cljc`. I didn't know how else to import the `defparser` macro, so I gave up on making the code `cljc` and kept it `cljs`.\r\n\r\nSince you didn't add any ClojureScript-only code so far you probably won't have any problem after following steps 1 and 2. Then you can run `lein test` to try out your new test case.",
      "performed_via_github_app":null
    },
